00:34:43.140 --> 00:34:46.440
So when I write stories,
this is what they look like.

00:34:46.440 --> 00:34:47.740
Yes, that's right.

00:34:47.740 --> 00:34:50.020
I write in a visual
format called thumbnails

00:34:50.020 --> 00:34:51.680 position:56%
which is what you see on the screen.

00:34:51.680 --> 00:34:55.480
So a thumbnail simply means like a
rough draft version or a blueprint

00:34:55.480 --> 00:34:57.770
or a sketch of every single page

00:34:57.770 --> 00:34:59.880
where you're indicating
the panel borders.

00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:01.730
The characters are stick figures.

00:35:01.730 --> 00:35:03.420
All of the dialog is there.

00:35:03.420 --> 00:35:04.720
All of the sound effects are there.

00:35:04.720 --> 00:35:08.810
And this is a great way for me
to see how comics are paced out.

00:35:08.810 --> 00:35:10.110
And as you guys saw
with the reading,

00:35:10.110 --> 00:35:13.570
there's a lot of silent panels and
there's a lot of sort of panels

00:35:13.570 --> 00:35:16.740
where a sound effect and the
pictures do a lot of the talking.

00:35:16.740 --> 00:35:18.040
So that's how write.

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.960
This is how my ideas come out
off my head and onto the page.

00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:23.980
And then once I am done with
those, I've done an entire book

00:35:23.980 --> 00:35:25.700
