Hi.

00:49:07.680 --> 00:49:11.510
&gt;&gt; Do you ever write out the script

00:49:11.510 --> 00:49:15.120
of what people are saying
before you draw the comics?

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:18.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Sometimes I do,
sometimes I will sit down and type

00:49:18.140 --> 00:49:20.710
out dialog just because
I can hear it

00:49:20.710 --> 00:49:22.750
in my head faster than
I can draw it.

00:49:22.750 --> 00:49:26.410 position:56%
But for the most part, like I showed
you guys, my scripts are thumbnails.

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:29.330
So they are just sort of
the grid of different panels

00:49:29.330 --> 00:49:31.160
and then the characters'
heads almost need

00:49:31.160 --> 00:49:32.930
to be there sometimes
before I could figure

00:49:32.930 --> 00:49:34.270
out what's coming out
of their mouths.

00:49:34.270 --> 00:49:37.190
I need to see it in order
to be able to hear it.

00:49:37.190 --> 00:49:40.020
But yes, I do have a notebook
and I'm always listening

00:49:40.020 --> 00:49:42.390
to people taking around
me and just the way

00:49:42.390 --> 00:49:45.110
that people talk sometimes
gives me ideas.

00:49:45.110 --> 00:49:47.390
So, you never know guys.

00:49:47.390 --> 00:49:48.690
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:49:48.690 --> 00:49:49.990
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Sure.

00:49:49.990 --> 00:49:51.290
Hi.

00:49:51.290 --> 00:49:53.260
&gt;&gt; Other than in "Smile" and
"Sisters," which character

00:49:53.260 --> 00:49:56.260
in your book represents
you the best?

00:49:56.260 --> 00:49:58.970
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: So you mean in
my memoirs or in my fictional work?

00:49:58.970 --> 00:50:00.320
&gt;&gt; In your fictional work.

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:03.560 position:56%
