00:50:21.330 --> 00:50:24.550
&gt;&gt; What inspired you to
write about your family?

00:50:24.550 --> 00:50:26.680
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Them.

00:50:26.680 --> 00:50:30.040
We have so many stories and I
mean the reason I started writing

00:50:30.040 --> 00:50:32.540
about my life was I have
this horrible dental accident

00:50:32.540 --> 00:50:36.000
when I was 11 and it was a story
I was telling people constantly.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:37.700
So people would be like,
"What happened to your teeth,"

00:50:37.700 --> 00:50:39.880
and I'd be like, "Let me tell
you what happened on my teeth."

00:50:39.880 --> 00:50:44.590 position:56%
And then as I got older, the fake
teeth that I had in my mouth started

00:50:44.590 --> 00:50:47.670
to turn a little bit gray so
sometimes people are like,

00:50:47.670 --> 00:50:49.290
"What's wrong with the teeth
in front of your mouth?

00:50:49.290 --> 00:50:50.590
They look different."

00:50:50.590 --> 00:50:53.020
So I had to explain and every
time I saw a different dentist,

00:50:53.020 --> 00:50:55.580
I had to explain and I was like
I have explained this story

00:50:55.580 --> 00:50:59.510
so may times, what if I just
like wrote the whole thing down?

00:50:59.510 --> 00:51:02.090
Yeah. That way, I wouldn't
have to explain it so much.

00:51:02.090 --> 00:51:05.750 position:56%
So I did. I just wrote my story down
and I realized that it's a great way

00:51:05.750 --> 00:51:07.700
to sort of deal with your memories

00:51:07.700 --> 00:51:09.570
and like stuff that's
troubling you even.

00:51:09.570 --> 00:51:13.840 position:56%
You can write it down and then you
feel better about it afterwards, so.

00:51:13.840 --> 00:51:15.140
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:51:15.140 --> 00:51:16.440
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Sure.

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:17.740
&gt;&gt; Hi.

00:51:17.740 --> 00:51:19.040
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Hi.

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:22.330
&gt;&gt; If you're like writing a
story about your true life then

00:51:22.330 --> 00:51:25.360
if you're trying to
remember what they're saying,

00:51:25.360 --> 00:51:30.060
do you have to like write the exact
thing or do you just like make it

00:51:30.060 --> 00:51:31.400
up if you don't remember

00:51:31.400 --> 00:51:33.890
but you have a general
idea of what they said?

00:51:33.890 --> 00:51:35.190
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Yes.

00:51:35.190 --> 00:51:36.490
That's exactly what I do.

00:51:36.490 --> 00:51:39.180
There is no way I could
possibly remember the exact words

00:51:39.180 --> 00:51:40.510
that we said to each other.

00:51:40.510 --> 00:51:43.930
Although, I mean you guys have
access, I'm sure, to like videos

00:51:43.930 --> 00:51:46.590
that your parents have been taking
since you're a little kid, right?

00:51:46.590 --> 00:51:48.460
And I have just a few of those.

00:51:48.460 --> 00:51:50.340
I only have one video
of myself as a kid

00:51:50.340 --> 00:51:53.350
because my grandfather
had this big video camera.

00:51:53.350 --> 00:51:56.830
It's like five minutes of video
of me in my entire childhood.

00:51:56.830 --> 00:51:58.350
But I have a lot of photographs

00:51:58.350 --> 00:52:00.590
and that's how the writer
brain works is you're just

00:52:00.590 --> 00:52:02.460
like I can imagine
what we were saying

00:52:02.460 --> 00:52:04.850
to each other when we were young.

00:52:04.850 --> 00:52:06.150
&gt;&gt; Oh, OK.

00:52:06.150 --> 00:52:07.450
Thanks.

00:52:07.450 --> 00:52:08.750
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Sure.

00:52:08.750 --> 00:52:12.050
&gt;&gt; Do you plan on writing any
sequels to any of your books

00:52:12.050 --> 00:52:14.110
like "Ghosts" or "Drama"?

00:52:14.110 --> 00:52:17.390
&gt;&gt; Raina Telgemeier: Sequels
are tricky, and I'm not somebody

00:52:17.390 --> 00:52:18.710
who thinks in terms of series.

00:52:18.710 --> 00:52:21.640
I'm really somebody who thinks
in terms of individual stories.

00:52:21.640 --> 00:52:25.280
So, I feel like I say everything
I want to say about the characters

00:52:25.280 --> 00:52:28.570 position:56%
and their lives and their situations
before the last page is turned.

00:52:28.570 --> 00:52:30.620
I don't like the idea
of cliffhangers.

00:52:30.620 --> 00:52:32.760
But that's not to say that
I would never write a story

00:52:32.760 --> 00:52:34.060
that had the same characters.

00:52:34.060 --> 00:52:36.600
So you know how "Smile" and
"Sisters" are companion books

00:52:36.600 --> 00:52:39.820
but it's not like exactly
what happened next.

00:52:39.820 --> 00:52:41.290
There's always a possibility
that I could do

00:52:41.290 --> 00:52:42.730
that with one of my
other stories too.

00:52:42.730 --> 00:52:44.030
&gt;&gt; OK. Thanks.

00:52:44.030 --> 00:52:45.360
